A variation on GMB&#39;s solution is simpler:

    select t.*
    from t
    where not exists (select 1
                      from t t2
                      where t.path like t2.path || &#39;/%&#39;
                     );

But the most efficient method uses `lag()`:

    select t.*
    from (select t.*, lag(path) over (order by path) as prev_path
          from t
         ) t
    where prev_path is null or path not like prev_path || &#39;/%&#39;;

[Here][1] is a db&lt;&gt;fiddle.

Note that this can use an index on `(path)` for the `lag()`.



  [1]: https://dbfiddle.uk/?rdbms=postgres_11&amp;fiddle=f0f3b21300e9e3e05de9f8ec01183410

