A few observations:

1. You want to use a locale of `en_US_POSIX`, an invariant locale that always works for ISO 8601 / RFC 3339 date strings. See [Technical Q&amp;A 1480][1].

2. If you want to use this formatter to convert a date back to a string like `2019-12-26T00:00Z`, you will want to:

 * Use `X` (or `ZZZZZ` or `XXXXX`) in your format string, not `Z` (see the “zone” section in the table at [Date Format Patterns][2] and you’ll see how these various time zone patterns, e.g. `Z`, `ZZZZZ`, and `X`, are interpreted); and 
 * Set the `timeZone` of the formatter to use Zulu/GMT/UTC.

Thus:

    @objc static func defaultDateFormat(_ format: String) -&gt; DateFormatter {
        let formatter = DateFormatter()
        formatter.locale = Locale(identifier: &quot;en_US_POSIX&quot;)
        formatter.timeZone = TimeZone(secondsFromGMT: 0)
        formatter.dateFormat = format
        return formatter
    }

And

    let df = DateFormatter.defaultDateFormat(&quot;yyyy-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mmX&quot;)
    let date = df.date(from: &quot;2019-12-26T00:00Z&quot;)

